Cell[TextData[{
 "The Schur basis is a basis of tensor-product space ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", "d", 
    RowBox[{"\[CircleTimes]", "n"}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "50a762de-c3c1-44de-9e74-8c73055cea89"],
 " in which the action of both symmetric and unitary groups on ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", "d", 
    RowBox[{"\[CircleTimes]", "n"}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "22f04265-25fb-4576-93ce-4c2ffc13c86e"],
 " is block-diagonalized. The dual Schur transform is a unitary \
transformation changing the computational basis of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubsuperscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", "d", 
    RowBox[{"\[CircleTimes]", "n"}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e5d2ab21-935c-42a6-ad4b-d51d3b2c0172"],
 " to the Schur basis. While the Schur transform algorithm of Bacon, Chuang \
and Harrow (2007) is based on the representations of the unitary group, the \
dual Schur transform algorithm uses the representations of the symmetric \
group. Technically, the Schur transform uses the Clebsch-Gordan transform of \
the unitary group whereas the dual Schur transform utilizes the generalized \
quantum Fourier transform over the symmetric group."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1521250694,ExpressionUUID->"c6bc9acf-0b6d-4d2d-9e90-27685f5214e3"],

