Saveable->False,
ScreenStyleEnvironment->"Working",
WindowSize->{900, 830},
WindowMargins->{{0, Automatic}, {Automatic, 0}},
WindowTitle->"Dual Quantum Schur Transform",
Visible->True,
TaggingRules->{
 "ModificationHighlight" -> False, "ColorType" -> "", "LinkTrails" -> "", 
  "ExampleCounter" -> 1, 
  "Openers" -> {
   "PrimaryExamplesSection" -> Open, "ExampleSection" -> {"0" -> Open}}, 
  "NewStyles" -> True, "CitationPopupData" -> {"2025", ""}, "ShowCitation" -> 
  False, "RootCaptions" -> "", "HeaderCoreAreaLink" -> {}, 
  "Metadata" -> {
   "built" -> "{2026, 5, 2, 18, 26, 57.832066}", 
    "history" -> {"14.3", "", "", ""}, "context" -> "QuantumMob`Q3`", 
    "keywords" -> {"Schur-Weyl duality", "Schur basis"}, 
    "specialkeywords" -> {}, "tutorialcollectionlinks" -> {}, "index" -> True,
     "label" -> "Quantum Mob/ Q3 Tech Note", "language" -> "en", "paclet" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3", "status" -> "None", "summary" -> 
    "The Schur basis is a basis of tensor-product space \
\\[ScriptCapitalV]_d^RowBox[{\\[CircleTimes, n}]] in which the action of both \
symmetric and unitary groups on \\[ScriptCapitalV]_d^RowBox[{\\[CircleTimes, \
n}]] is block-diagonalized. The dual Schur transform is a unitary \
transformation changing the computational basis of \
\\[ScriptCapitalV]_d^RowBox[{\\[CircleTimes, n}]] to the Schur basis. While \
the Schur transform algorithm of Bacon, Chuang and Harrow (2007) is based on \
the representations of the unitary group, the dual Schur transform algorithm \
uses the representations of the symmetric group. Technically, the Schur \
transform uses the Clebsch-Gordan transform of the unitary group whereas the \
dual Schur transform utilizes the generalized quantum Fourier transform over \
the symmetric group. Consider a system of n identical particles, each of \
which is associated with a d-dimensional Hilbert space \\[ScriptCapitalV]_d. \
The Schur-Weyl duality assures that the tensor-product space \
\\[ScriptCapitalV]_d^RowBox[{\\[CircleTimes, n}]] may be decomposed as \
\\[ScriptCapitalV]_d^RowBox[{\\[CircleTimes, \
n}]]=\\[CirclePlus]_\\[Lambda]\\[ScriptCapitalY]^\\[Lambda]\\[CircleTimes]\\[\
ScriptCapitalW]^\\[Lambda] , where \\[ScriptCapitalY]^\\[Lambda] and \
\\[ScriptCapitalW]^\\[Lambda] are irreducible representation spaces \
associated with integer partition \\[Lambda] of the symmetric and unitary \
groups, respectively. The Schur basis {TemplateBox[{RowBox[{\\[Lambda], ,, \
RowBox[{SubscriptBox[y, \\[Lambda]], , SubscriptBox[w, \\[Lambda]]}]}]}, Ket] \
} is a basis of \\[ScriptCapitalV]_d^RowBox[{\\[CircleTimes, n}]] consistent \
with the above decomposition such that standard Young tableaux y_\\[Lambda] \
and Weyl tableaux w_\\[Lambda] label the basis vectors in \\[ScriptCapitalY]^\
\\[Lambda] and \\[ScriptCapitalW]^\\[Lambda], respectively. Let \
\\[ScriptCapitalM]^\\[Mu] be a permutation module of content \\[Mu]: \
\\[ScriptCapitalM]^\\[Mu]=Span {TemplateBox[{RowBox[{SubscriptBox[i, 1], ,, \
SubscriptBox[i, 2], ,, \\[Ellipsis], ,, SubscriptBox[i, n]}]}, \
Ket]:content({i_ 1,i_ 2,\\[Ellipsis],i_n})=\\[Mu]}. It can be rewritten in \
terms of permutations as \
\\[ScriptCapitalM]^\\[Mu]=Span{\\[CapitalPi](g)TemplateBox[{\\[Mu]}, \
Ket]:g\\[Element]\\[ScriptCapitalS]_n}, where TemplateBox[{\\[Mu]}, \
Ket]:=TemplateBox[{RowBox[{UnderscriptBox[UnderscriptBox[RowBox[{1, ,, 1, ,, \
1}], \\[UnderBrace]], SubscriptBox[\\[Mu], 1]], ,, \
UnderscriptBox[UnderscriptBox[RowBox[{2, ,, 2, ,, 2}], \\[UnderBrace]], \
SubscriptBox[\\[Mu], 2]], ,, \\[Ellipsis], ,, \
UnderscriptBox[UnderscriptBox[RowBox[{d, ,, d, ,, d}], \\[UnderBrace]], \
SubscriptBox[\\[Mu], d]]}]}, Ket] .", "synonyms" -> {}, "tabletags" -> {}, 
    "title" -> "Dual Quantum Schur Transform", "titlemodifier" -> "", 
    "metadescription" -> "", "windowtitle" -> "Dual Quantum Schur Transform", 
    "type" -> "Tech Note", "uri" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/DualQuantumSchurTransform"}},
